    <h1>How We Review Tools</h1>
    <div class="page-meta">Will Denholm · Last updated April 2026</div>

    <p>DataToolIndex exists because most tool comparison sites are either written by marketing teams at the vendors, produced by journalists who've never touched the product, or generated by AI that scraped vendor documentation. The result is comparison content that's accurate about surface features but useless when you're actually trying to make a buy decision.</p>

    <p>Every review on this site is written from the perspective of a B2B industrial pricing analyst who has evaluated and used these tools in production environments. Where I have direct experience, I say so. Where I rely on documentation or community sources, I say that too.</p>

    <h2>The Author</h2>

    <p><strong>Will Denholm</strong> — 7+ years as a B2B industrial pricing analyst. My day job involves building pricing variance models (list/floor/target/actual, LogMid vs. ArthAvg comparisons, DVP% tracking by customer tier), managing quote approval workflows, and building analytics on top of ERPs. I have directly evaluated and used in production:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Pricing platforms:</strong> Pricefx, PROS, Vendavo (evaluated), Zilliant (evaluated)</li>
      <li><strong>BI tools:</strong> Power BI (primary), Sigma (evaluated), Alteryx (active use), Tableau (evaluated)</li>
      <li><strong>Data infrastructure:</strong> Snowflake, dbt, Power Query/M language (deep expertise)</li>
      <li><strong>Data integration:</strong> Fivetran (live), Airbyte (evaluated)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>For tools outside my direct experience, I consult practitioner community sources (dbt Slack, Modern Data Stack Discord, vendor-neutral forums) and clearly flag where the assessment is secondhand.</p>

    <h2>Editorial Principles</h2>

    <div class="principle-grid">
      <div class="principle">
        <div class="principle-label">No Paid Placement</div>
        <p>Vendors cannot pay to appear in rankings, receive higher ratings, or be featured in use-case comparisons. The order tools appear in shortlists reflects the evaluation criteria disclosed on each page.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="principle">
        <div class="principle-label">Verified Pricing</div>
        <p>Every pricing table is verified directly against the vendor's public pricing page, with a verification date. Pricing changes frequently — if you find a discrepancy, the vendor site is authoritative.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="principle">
        <div class="principle-label">Affiliate Disclosure</div>
        <p>Some pages include affiliate links. These are disclosed at the top of every page that contains them. Affiliate relationships do not influence ratings, rankings, or which tools appear in comparisons.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="principle">
        <div class="principle-label">Experience Over Marketing</div>
        <p>Where I have direct production experience with a tool, that experience takes precedence over vendor documentation. Where I don't, I say so explicitly and rely on secondhand sources.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="principle">
        <div class="principle-label">Dated Content</div>
        <p>Every review includes a "last verified" date. Tool features, pricing, and market position change frequently. Reviews are refreshed monthly (tool pages) and weekly (use-case comparisons).</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>How Tool Reviews Are Structured</h2>

    <p>Each tool review follows this structure, in order:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Verdict first:</strong> The opening paragraph states whether I recommend the tool and under what conditions. No burying the lead.</li>
      <li><strong>What it is:</strong> A clear, jargon-minimal explanation of what the tool does, who makes it, and how it's positioned.</li>
      <li><strong>Verified pricing:</strong> A table of current pricing tiers, verified against the vendor site, with a date.</li>
      <li><strong>Features:</strong> The capabilities that matter for the buyer audience — not a feature dump from the vendor's marketing page.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for:</strong> The specific buyer profiles where this tool is the right answer.</li>
      <li><strong>Not ideal for:</strong> The specific buyer profiles where another tool is likely better. If I can't identify these, the review is incomplete.</li>
      <li><strong>Alternatives:</strong> A comparison table of the nearest alternatives with a one-line differentiation. Internal links go to full reviews.</li>
      <li><strong>FAQ:</strong> Questions that practitioners actually ask, answered directly.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How Use-Case Comparisons Are Structured</h2>

    <p>Use-case pages answer a specific buyer question: "What's the best X for Y?" They follow this structure:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Direct answer first:</strong> The first paragraph names the winner and under what conditions. Readers should not have to scroll to find out what we recommend.</li>
      <li><strong>Ranked shortlist:</strong> Tools ordered by fit for the specific use case, not alphabetically or by market share.</li>
      <li><strong>Evaluation criteria:</strong> Explicit weights for the factors that matter for this specific use case. Different use cases weight different things.</li>
      <li><strong>What to avoid:</strong> Common mistakes buyers make — including buying a tool when a simpler solution would work.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What This Site Is Not</h2>

    <div class="callout">
      This is not a comprehensive software directory. We cover tools I have genuine expertise evaluating. A tool being absent from this site does not mean it's bad — it means I don't have enough experience with it to review it honestly.
    </div>

    <p>This is not a news site. We don't cover funding rounds, acquisitions, or product launches unless they directly affect the buy decision (e.g., a pricing change or a significant feature addition).</p>

    <p>This is not a forum or community. The reviews represent one practitioner's assessment. Your context will differ. Use these reviews as a starting point, not a final word.</p>

    <h2>Contact and Corrections</h2>

    <p>If you find a pricing error, a factual mistake, or a tool you think deserves coverage, the most reliable way to flag it is via the GitHub repository for this site. Corrections are prioritized and applied quickly — outdated pricing information is the failure mode I care most about avoiding.</p>
